[Project] Hoiktronics: Teleport Hub for a Large World

  1. DicemanX Brain of Cthulhu

    Start a Conversation
    My current world is loaded with teleporters at home base because I have quite a few points of interest that I like visiting. However, the set-up is a bit messy, especially since I sometimes have to look up the signs at each teleporter to see where they lead.

    I thus decided to take advantage of recent mechanisms to build a gigantic teleport center that can send the player to potentially hundreds of locations from *one* starting teleporter. The idea is to have a directory and a keypad - once a certain destination is found in the directory and its associated alphanumeric key, that key needs to then be entered in a keypad and the teleporter needs to be activated by a switch to send the player to the desired destination. When returning via the teleporter, the player returns to the starting teleporter in the hub.

    Here's the set-up:



    Here's the wiring:



    The wiring is all green around the hub teleporters, which allows for red or blue wires to be used to connect the teleporters in the hub to distant teleporters. This should make it very easy to connect all the destinations to the hub.

    The signs at the bottom comprise the directory where the player can look up the alphanumeric codes for various destinations. There is one sign per letter, and looking at that sign the player would see:

    Directory A:
    A1: Mushroom Farm
    A2: Flower Farm
    A3: Wall of Flesh Autofarm
    A4: Moon Event Autofarm
    etc.

    If the player wishes to travel to the Wall of Flesh Autofarm for instance, the player would enter A on the bottom pad and 3 on the top pad, and then activate the teleporter between the pads. The letter dictates which tier the player will travel to via a system of hoiks; the number dictates which teleporter the player will be hoiked to in that tier.

    When the player travels to the selected teleporter in the hub, the player will activate pressure plates along the way that will shut off the letter and number that were activated, automatically resetting the pad. When the player returns from the player's destination to the teleporter in the hub, an up hoik pushes the player into a waist-high bottom hoik, which hoiks the player to a down hoik, and a teleporter at the bottom returns the player to the starting teleporter in the hub close to the keypads.

    The system is designed so that if no letters or numbers are chosen, the player will eventually end up in the down hoik on the right and will be sent back to the original teleporter.

    In the picture above, I connected 3 of the 30 teleporters to do tests: if A7, B9, or C2 are entered into the pads, then the player will end up in one of the three teleporters connected to the teleporters in the hub. This is to illustrate how teleporters in the world would be connected to those in the hub.

    I will show a video of this in action, although I have to determine whether I will incorporate this into my main world - it will take a lot of rewiring work if I do.

After I actually hook up this hub in my main world (decided to go ahead with it) I'll compress if there's space.

    It might make it slightly more convenient to have an outer array of teleporters for connection purposes, but if it comes at the expense of consistent auto-resets or return loops, then of course I'll stick with the current layout. Still, it's worth a look! The hoik system is currently pretty stable whereas other configurations I tried were too sensitive to player position on the teleporter, so re-engineering the loops might be quite troublesome. Plus if I end up with more than 30 destinations it'll be easier to just keep adding tiers whereas outer arrays are not so easily expanded.

    The only way to save on wiring is to run the green wires in a vertical straight line through all the teleporters and pressure plates - is that what you mean? I avoid this for a couple of reasons, the main reason being that when I present a wiring diagram I try to make the wiring as clear as possible even if it takes a bit more wiring to do so. Passing the green wires through teleporters in the hub, while harmless, might confuse certain viewers that are not aware that green wires are last priority, or are not aware of what happens when multiple teleporters are linked with wire.

    The shifting of pressure plates won't work unfortunately - the pressure plate cannot be on the side because it won't trigger during the up hoiking (it also won't trigger on the right side of the teleporter). It has to be in the middle of the teleporter. Also your shift of green wire doesn't actually save on any green wiring since it doesn't really matter if the vertical stretch is directly between the pressure plate and the actuated hoik in the next tier, or 2 blocks to the left of the plate and actuated hoik tooth as you illustrate. Your green wiring does look more aesthetically pleasing though .

    Still, you nicely show the vertical compression and how the final structure can be more compact than what I initially posted (and the down hoik teeth still line up properly)! Further compression will be possible because the half the blue and red wires from the teleporters can run in the opposite direction - it will be possible to compress a further 2 blocks between tiers.

  16. DicemanX Brain of Cthulhu

    Start a Conversation
    I put the initial hub aside and constructed a vastly superior hub after reorienting the set-up 90 degrees:



    This hub is superior for two important reasons:

    1) There is no longer any sensitivity when it comes to the player position on the return teleporter. This is due to the fact that upon returning the player finds himself in the middle of a head-high top hoik with no spaces in between teeth, guaranteeing being hoiked to the right.
    2) There is no longer a down hoik which can sometimes mess up hoiking the player downwards.

    It doesn't appear that a further vertical compression is possible because the up hoik teeth will not align.

    Now the only thing left is to make the pad area a little nicer and the green wiring a bit more compact.

  18. DicemanX Brain of Cthulhu

    Start a Conversation
    Danke said: ↑
    Early world download? Horizontal compression is still possible.
    Click to expand...
    Compression has to come in threes to make sure the up hoik teeth line up with the horizontal hoiks, so it looks like we are at the limit. Up hoiks don't always need to be spaced 2 apart (they can alternate 2 apart and 1 apart), but in this set-up it seems they do unfortunately. The transition from head-high top hoik into an up hoik is particularly problematic. You're welcome to try to see if there's anything I missed for horizontal compression (world download below).

    Vertical compression is possible at the expense of return teleporter sensitivity (if compressed further, player gets stuck if player teleports from the edge of a return teleporter). In the current configuration, there seems to be no teleporter sensitivity at all.

    World download:

    http://www.filedropper.com/computerworldv2

    Danke said: ↑
    Did my best, took slightly longer due to issues with the hoiks:

    Excellent idea eliminating three of the up hoik columns! I tested it with actual return teleporters and it works perfectly. Nice catch! I will credit you in my upcoming video for the improvement to this hub, because it looks like the limit has been reached on the compression.

    I will change one thing though - better to have a wider head-high top hoik (the way I had it initially, with an extra pair of top hoik teeth on either side above the three teeth directly above reach teleporter) otherwise the player will get stuck unless they teleport from inside the three wide tile of space above the return teleporter. This will eliminate all return teleporter sensitivity at the expense of 6 vertical lines of space.

    Of course it's ultimately the builder's choice which version to build should they choose to build this hub in their world.

    Here's a snapshot of the build I will go with, using your compression idea (EDIT - changed my mind; better set-up below):



    Now it's time for the long tedious task of actually connecting the teleporters to everything in my world (I have 20 teleport destinations to connect, and a lot of wiring to clean up). Also need to shoot a video of the fishing autofarm for you Danke!

    EDIT: Just to illustrate teleporter sensitivity:



    If a player teleports from that position, the player will get stuck on the teeth upon the return to the hub. This sort of problem appears on the left hand side only - if the player juts out over the edge of the return teleporter on the right, they'll still get pushed into the up hoik.

    Curiously, I tried this:



    I expanded the left side of the teleporters, and all of a sudden the player doesn't make contact with the pressure plate anymore, leading to the player getting stuck. For some strange reason that extra tooth on the left is preventing pressure plate activation, and yet if an extra tooth is added on the right then it's fine (as shown in my first pic above).

    EDIT2:

    OK problem solved:



    I shifted all the pressure plates to the left 1 tile and all works again. This set-up saves three vertical lines of space compared to my first pic above. This is an even better position for the pressure plate because it prevents a second activation of the plate if the player teleports in from the far left.
